u(x,y)
u(e,1)=?
u(x,y)
xu_{x}+u_{y}=1,\;\;u(x,0)=2\ln(x),\quad x>1.
u(x,y) = u(x(s),y(s)) = f(s)
x'(s) = x
y'(s) = 1
u(x,0) = 2 \ln(x)
y=0 \implies s = 0
\dfrac{df}{ds} = \dfrac{\partial u}{\partial x} \dfrac{dx}{ds} + \dfrac{\partial u}{\partial y} \dfrac{dy}{ds} = x'(s) u_x +y'(s) u_y = xu_x + u_y
x(s) = c_1 e^s; \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\, y(s) = s \,\,\,\,\,\,\, f'(s) = 1 \implies f(s) = s + f(0)
f(0) = 2 \ln(x(0)) = 2 \ln(c_1) = f(0) \implies f(0) = 2 \ln(c_1)
f(0) = 2 \ln(xe^{-y}) \implies u(x,y) = s + 2 \ln(xe^{-y})
= y + 2 \ln(x) - 2y
 = 2\ln(x) - y
